<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12069b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12069b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12069b"> 69(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Send turbot to bishop / to get power to confess</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Cependant, le pr&eacute;lat ne demeurait pas toujours sensible &agrave; la politesse que lui faisaient les moines; c&apos;est ainsi qu&apos;en mai 1646 &laquo;un estur- <font color="green">[250]</font> geon parfaitement beau, gros et grand&raquo;, fut p&eacute;ch&eacute; entre le Mont et Tombelaine, il fut apport&eacute; &laquo;tout vif, dans la cuisine du monast&egrave;re et l&agrave; y fut mesur&eacute;, ayant 9 pieds et demi de longueur et gros &agrave; proportion. Le R. P. Dom Dominique Huillard, prieur, de l&apos;advis de la communaut&eacute; l&apos;envoya, d&egrave;s le bon matin, &agrave; Messire Roger d&apos;Aumont, r&eacute;v&eacute;rendissime et illustrissime &eacute;v&ecirc;que d&apos;Avranches, lequel eut fort agr&eacute;able ce pr&eacute;sent qui m&eacute;ritait bien aussi estre agr&eacute;&eacute;, croyant par l&agrave; obliger le seigneur &agrave; aimer le monast&egrave;re et la Religion; mais l&apos;issue en a &eacute;t&eacute; diff&eacute;rente ainsi que je le dirai en son lieu <font color="green">[1]</font>.&raquo; <br><font color="green">[1]</font> Les moines voulaient obtenir de l&apos;&eacute;v&ecirc;que l&apos;autorisation de confesser tous ceux qui se pr&eacute;senteraient &agrave; eux; ils engag&egrave;rent &agrave; ce sujet des conversations avec l&apos;&eacute;v&ecirc;que d&apos;Avranches et c&apos;est au cours de ces n&eacute;gociations qu&apos;ils offrirent le beau turbot. Ils en furent pour leurs frais. Le 2 mai 1647, Monseigneur d&apos;Avranches d&eacute;fendit aux religieux d&apos; &laquo;ouyr les confessions du peuple et invalida toutes les absolutions&raquo;. Cette mesure irrita les moines &agrave; un degr&eacute; que l&apos;on ne saurait imaginer. Aussi firent-ils sur son nom un jeu de mots; ils l&apos;appel&egrave;rent Rodomont. <br><font color="green">[Still, the prelate was not always susceptible to the politeness shown him by the monks; thus in May 1646 &ldquo;a perfectly beautiful, heavy and big <mark>sturgeon</mark>&rdquo; was caught between the Mont and Tombelaine. It was brought &ldquo;all alive, into the kitchen of the monastery and was there measured, being 9 feet and a half in length and big in proportion. The Reverend Father Dom Dominique Seuillard, prior, on the advice of the community, sent it the next morning to Monsieur Roger d&apos;Aumont, the very reverend and illustrious bishop of Avranches, where it was very gratefully received, this gift which was worth the gratitude, because he felt that this would oblige the Lord to love the monastery and religion; but the results were rather different as I will tell in its proper place.[1]</font> <br>1. <mark>The monks wanted from the bishop the privilege of being able to hear confession of everybody who came to them; they started negotiations with the bishop of Avranches for that purpose and it was during these that they offered him this beautiful fish</mark>. It was in vain. On May 2, 1647, His Grace of Avranches forbade the monks to &ldquo;hear confessions of the people and he invalidated all their absolutions.&rdquo; This decision irritated the monks to a degree that cannot be imagined. So they made a pun on his name: they called him Rodomont.] <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 250-1</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
